{"/service/ndnp/mb/batch_mb_basil_ver01/data/sn83020847/00517170847/1946062001/0349.xml":{"full_text":"GOVERNMENT MEN\nAIR OPPOSING IDEAS\nON PRICE OUTLOOK\nInflation and Deflation Are\nBoth Forecast Ayres\nAlarmed by Recent Pace of\nOPA Advances\nMall Street CorreMpondenre\nOf The Springfield Republican\nNaw York, .lune 17 A few\n\u2022\u2018blue, chip\" industrial stocks having\na thin market closed with itvegular\nprice changes of a point or more,\nbut. after slowly gaining ground to\nmidday, the. industrial list ended down\na few cents on the average. Rails\nfinished a small fraction higher on\nthe average but also below the day\u2019s\nbest.\nA top government economist at\nWashington, declining to have his\nname used, was quoted today as say\ning after examining the course the\ncost of living is taking that to him\nthe trend is alarming This is in\nconflict with a dispatch from Wash\nington last week that government\neconomists are now quietly planning\nto take care of deflation expected to\ncome in a matter of six months or\nan: that the danger of postwar in\nflation was passed in the late spring:\nand that from now on a greater\ndanger lies in too-rapid deflation.\nCited Buyer\u2019s Resistance\nIn last weeks Washington dis\npatch government economic experts\ndeclared that the danger signals point\ning to deflation instead of Inflation\nwere growing buyers resistance Io\nhigh prices and inferior merchandise\nThe unnamed government economist\nquoted today attributed his alarm\nover the cost-of-living trend to the\nquickening pace of OPA price in\ncrease grants.\nThere seems to be more in the lat\nter viewpoint than the first. The\ndecline in savings and the increase\nin conversion of government bonds\ninto cash are the result of the wide\nspread labor troubles since the be\nginning of the year. But the worst\nof the strike trouble appears to be I\nbehind. Only today the director of\nthe United States Employment serv\nice stated that the country had\npassed its peak of postwar unem\nployment. predicting that from now\non things would got better.\"\nThere is no guess work, however,\nabout the quickening pace of price\nincrea.se grants by the OPA. The\nadministrations hold-the-price-line\nprogram was scrapped when the. steel\ncompanies were allowed by the OPA\nto raise their selling prices to offset\nthe increase granted in wages. Sub\nsequently that pattern was followed\nin settling other strikes. Within the\npast two weeks, not including to\nday\u2019s rise in butter, cheese and con\ndensed milk prices, the OPA has al\nlowed no less than 52 price increases.\nAyres Raps Truman\nLeonard P. Ayres. Cleveland econo\nmist. pointing to the \"increasing ac\nceleration\" 'n the price advance of\nthe 889 different wholesale commodi\nties included in the Bureau of Labor\nprice index says: \"This is a dis\nquieting development because it indi-I\nca\u2019es that the forces making for in\nflation are becoming increasingly\npowerful.\"\n\"In at least a major degree the\ncontinuing and accelerated advance\nin the upward price trend must be\nattributed ihe ill-advised and mis\ntaken attempts of the government at\nWashington to forestall and offset the\ndreaded deflation which they imag\nined would follow the. coming peace.\nThe President invited the wage ad\nvances and thereby invited the strikes\nwhich stimulated inflation. The wage\nincreases are forcing upward the\ncost of production and they in turn\nforce prices upward. We have not\nyet completed even the first wave:\nof strikes for higher wages.\"\nWall street\u2019s private information\ntoday from Washington is that ex-'\npectations there are for a \"spectacu\nlar\" advance in prices during the\nnext three months, partly as a re\nsult of weakening of OPA price con\ntrols. and partly because the recent\naccelerated pace at which the OPA\nhas allowed price advances that the!\noutlook today is for a secondary\nwave of demands for higher wages\nto offset the mounting cost of liv\ning.\nSeems Just Plain Dumb\nWith the unprecedented business\noutlook this country had when the\nwar ended less than a year ago. it\nseems just plain dumb that we should\ntoday he heading in the same direc\ntion taken after the first World war\nended. Today no one can tell how\nmuch further we are going to travel\non the road to inflation, or. what\nthe final results will be. But todas\nonly the timing is uncertain. The\ntraffic lights ahead definitely are not\ngreen.\nIn the meantime the important\nthing to watch at Washington is th* 5\npending price-control legislation. The\nbest guess today is that the life of\nthe price administration will be pro\nlonged but that It will operate with\ngreatly shorn powers.\nMembers of the New York Stock\nexchange are being asked for a spe\ncial report on the number of margin\naccounts on their books, the purpose\nof the reports being to help the\nexchange and the federal authorities\nJn their continuing of studies on the\nsecurities markets. When the stock\nmarket was put on a cash basis on\nJanuary 21 the rule was mtide that\nno stocks could be \"bought\u201d on mar\ngin. hut that stocks then carried on\nmargin could be held until liquidated.\nR. L. BARNUM.\nPARAMOUNT PICTURES\nVOTES 2-FOR-l SPLIT\nNew York. June IS\u2014(AP)\u2014Stock\nholders of Paramount Pictures, inc.,\nat the annual meeting today author\nised a two-for-one split of present\ncommon stock.\nThere are presently 4,455,800 shares\nnt authorized common stork, of wh\u2019ch\n3 752,136 shares are outstanding. The\nplan involves the issuance of one ad\nditional share for each share held\nand the authorization of additional\nshares t.o increase the total author\nized common stock to 9.000.000 shares\nof SI.OO par value.\nThe splitup is effective July 8 to\n\u2022tock of record June 35.\nBarney Balaban, president, told\n\u2022rockholders earnings are. continuing\nat the rate reported tor the first\nquarter of 1946. For the March quar\nter net profit was $11,587,000. equal\nto $3.09 a share on the 3.751.136 com\nmon shares outstanding, compared\nwith earnings last year equal to $1.07\na share.\nST REGIS PAPER BUYS\nPROPERTIES IN SOUTH\nNew York. June 18\u2014(API\u2014St Regis\nPaper Co. has purchased Florida Pulp\nand Paper Co. of Pensacola. Fla.. In\na deal involving approximately $7.-\n500.000, a Joint announcement said\ntoday.\nPurchase by St Regis of an equity\nof roughly 25 per cent in Alabama\nPulp and Paper Co., an hitherto in\ndependent company with the same\nofficers as Florida Pulp, was also an\nnounced.\nThe transaction marked entry of\nSt Regis into the Kraft pulp and pa-\nFINANCIAL\nper Industry in the South. Paper\nproducing properties of the company,\none of the largest domestic? paper\nproduct# manufacturers, have been\nconfined Io the Northeast and Pacific\nNorthwest.\nRAILS TAKE LEAD\nIN QUIET MARKET\nLate Sales Cut Early Gains\nPutting Numerous Leaders\nin Minus Column 60-\nStock Average Up .2\nNew York. June 17 \u2014(AP) \u2014Slocks\ngenerally followed the rails when the\nlatter touched another 15-year peak in\ntoday\u2019s market but late profit caah-\nIng reduced most early gains of frac\ntions to a point or more and put nu\nmerous leaders in the minua column.\nAt Iha l, the carriers were Ihe day\u2019s\nbeat performtra Buying herg again\nwas based mainly on hopes for a\nfreight-rate increase. Steels. bol\nstered by expanding ingot output, did\nwell the greater'part of the day al\nthough the majority of these barked\ndown at the last. Inflation psychol\nogy. stemming from rising living costs\nand wages, brokers said, was respon\nsible for some purchasing. Many cus\ntomers stood aside, however, to await\nprice control developments in Con\ngress.\nDealings were relatively quiet\nthroughout. Advances had a shade\nthe best of the argument at Ihe close.\nTransfers of 1.020.000 shares compared\nwith 980.000 Friday.\nThe A s.sori.tied Press GO-stock com\nposite was up .2 of a point at 81.7.\nThe rail average finished up .3 at\n51.2 which equaled the top figure since\n1931 established last Thursday. Of\n969 issues registering, 408 rose and\n366 declined.\nBonds were irregularly improved.\nAt Chicago grain trading was virtu\nally at a standstill with futures at\nceilings. Cotton rallied and ended up\n20 cents to sl.lO a bale.\nAmong curb advancers were Casco\nProducts. Pharis Tire. Textron, Cata\nlin Co., and General Finance. Turn\nover here was 140.000 shares against\n450.000 in the previous session.\nEXCHANGE TO REPLY\nTO OHIO OBJECTIONS\nReasons for Listing Kaiser-\nFrazer in Curb Market Will\nBe Told at Earliest Pos\nsible Moment\u2019\nNew York. June 18\u2014 (AP)\u2014 The\nNew York Curb exchange will forward\nto the Ohio State division of securi\nties \"at the earliest possible moment\"\nits reasons for listing the shares of\nKaiser-Frazer Corp.. Edwin Posner,\nexchange president, said today.\nErnest Cornell, chief of the Ohio\nagency, yesterday wrote to the ex\nchange threatening to suspend it\nfrom Ohio trading because of its list\ning of Kaiser-Frazer stock, which\nCornell termed \"unseasoned securities\nwithout. earnings.\u201d\nPosner issued the following siate\nment:\n\"The New York Curb exchange\nreceived only this afternoon (Tues\nday) the letter of the division of\nsecurities of the state of Ohio re\nlating to the listing on this exchange\nof shares of the Kaiser-Frazer Corp.,\nwhich letter was the subject of news\npaper comment yesterday.\n\"Mr Ernest Cornell, chairman of the\nOhio division, requests in his letter\ncomplete details, the various steps\nand reasons why the exchange listed\nthe shares. He states that a full and\ncomplete statement from the ex\nchange may make unnecessary the\ncalling of a hearing or the taking of\niaction under the general code of\nI Ohio.\n\"Such report will be prepared and\nforwarded at the earliest possible\nmoment.\u201d\nCorneil has objected to the listing\nof 1.800.000 shares of Kaiser-Frazer.\ni offered in January at $20.50 a share\nafter 1,700.000 shares originally is-\ni sued had been offered and approved\nin Ohio for sale at $lO in September.\n1945. The Curb exchange recently\n[admitted all of the automobile com\npany's shares to listing.\nDIVIDEND STATEMENTS\nKo^ario Mining\nNew York. June 12 (AP> Directors\nof New York Honduras Rosario Mining\nCo. declared an Interim dividend of $1.15\npayable June 28 to stock of record June\n18. A payment of 85 cents was made Ylarch\n,30. Declarations last year were 60 cents\nin March, 70 cents each in June and Sep\ntember and $1.50 In December.\nLehman Corp.\nLehman Corp, directors declared a divi\ndend of >5.4.5 a capital share payable June\n25 to stock of record June 18. Robert Leh\nman. president. said approximately 85 rep\nresented a distribution of net profits on\nsale of securities during the fiscal year\nended June 30. while approximately 45 cents\nwas on account of net ordinary income for\nthe fiscal year. 1n each of three previous\nquarters payments of 30 cents a share, were\nmade. On June 25, 1945. a special dividend\nof $2.60 was paid.\nDevoe, Raynoids Co.\nDirectors of Devoe Raynoid# Co., inc..\ndeclared dividends of 30 cents a share on\nclass \u201cA\" and 15 cents a share on class\n\u201cB\u201c common stock, payable July 1 to hold\ners of Record June 22. On April 1 payments\nof 20 cents on the class \u201cA\" and 10 cents\non the class '*B\" stock were made.\nSafeway Stores\nDirectors of Safeway Stores have de\nclared a dividend ot $1.25 a share on the\n5 per cent preferred stock, and a dividend\nof 25 cents a share on the $5 par value\ncommon stock, both payable July 1, 1946\nto stockholders of record at the close of\nbusiness June 18. The directors also author\nized the call for redemption nf 4452 shares\nof thia preferred stock for surrender to the\n1946 sinking fund.\nElectric Boat (\u2019p.\nBayonne. N. J.. June 12 (AP>\nStockholders of Electric Boat Co. at the\nannual me.eting today approved issue of new\npreferred stock to be paid as a dividend\non the basis of one preferred for each\nfour common. The new preferred will have\na stated value ot 850 a share, will be cu\nmulative as to dividends of $2 tier share an\nnually, and will be convertible into com\nmon stock ehare for share. The dividend\nis scheduled to be paid July 10 to common\nstork holders of record July 1. Distribution\nwill he made to approximately 5000 stock\nholders.\nInvesting Companies\nRid Ask\nAffiliated 7.05 8.36\nAm Business Shrs 5.46 5.98\nBond Inv Trust 10V\u00ab9 110.09\nBoston Fund 26.4 4 28.4.\u201d.\nCentury Shares Trust 34.6 R 37.29\nChemical Fund 16.\u00ab9 19.0'\nDividend Shares 1.89 2.07\nRaton Howard Bal Fd 27.8:: 29.76\nEaton Howard Stock Fd 18.1\"\u00bb 19.40\nFundamental Investors 18.28 20.08\n(\u2022roup Securities\nAviation Ih.Oo 10.99\nFully Administered 9.36 10.28\nI Inverting ,11.74 12.81\nI HR Equip 641 7.08\nRR Stocks 7.33 \u00ab.<F\nSteel 6 75 7.42\nIncorporated \u2019nvestors 33.05 35.54\nInv Man Fd inc 17.7 T\u00bb c r.\nMass Tnve\u00ab f Tiust 32 66 35.12\nMass Inv Tr 2 17.08 19.38\nNational Investors 13.64 14.75\nDiversified Inv Fd 14.66 1\u00ab.?o J\nGeorge Putnam Fd 17.93 19.28\nRATE PROBE REFUSED\nWashington, .lune 17\u2014 (AP) \u2014The\nInterstate Commerce commission to\nday refused a request by the Maritime\ncommission and the War Shipping ad\nministration for a broad investigation\nof railroad rates which are competi\ntive with domestic water carrier ratee.\nTHE SPRINGFIELD WEEKLY REPUBLICAN: SPRINGFIELD. MASS.: THURSDAY. JUNE 20, 1946\nSale of Stocks\n\u00bbw York Stock exchange\nNew York Cork exchange SOO,ono\nlloMon Stock exchange 17441\nN#t\nSale# In 100# High Ix>w Close Chg\nA\n5 Abbott Lab 73 71% 71% 2\nACT-Brill Mot 15% 15% 15%\nm Arma St! 43 48% 48'4 1\nI Adaina Exp 21% 31% 21\n1 Adama-Mlllia 5\u00ab 59 5\u00bb 2\n1 Addteesog-Miilt ~38 38 38 4-\n9 Admiral Corp 15% 15% t\u00bb%\n21 Air Reduction 54% 54% 54% 1%\n1.10 Ala A Vicks .129 129 )29 4-1\n3 Aldana Inc 47% 4\u00ab% 4