\nStocks Lose Three to Foui\nPoints in Depressing Day\nWall (orrospondence\nOf The Republican\nNew York. Jun? 18 Increasing\nuncertainties ahead for general buri--\nI ne#e apparently today got on rhe\nI nerves of holdert of stock*. FOllow\nng flrmneaa to noon, prices turned,\ndownward on increasing volume, with\njtbg market ending at the day's low\nprices. A considerable list of stocks\nclosed down from on? to three points\nwith Chrysler loemg four, du Pont 6%-\nIn reporting to the American pub\nic on its operations for the past\nyear, Johns-Manville says: \"Frankly.\nlike most American industries, we\ndid not accomplish nearly as much\nas we hoped to. and so, we ar? re\nporting about such things as man\npower shortages, strikes, production\ncuria,lm?nt and soms reasons for the\nbuilding shortage.\"\nThe company, it is reported, was\nfully prepared with a detailed pro\ngram for reemployment of veterans:\nthat it was readv to provide its share\nof jobs toward the goal of \"full em\nployment\u2019\u2019 but that the company\nfound itself as did many other in\ndustries unable to go to capacity pro\nduction largely because many war\nworkers accepted unemployment com\npensation supplied by government In\nstead of peacetime jobs\"; that \u201cto\nday. with more than 13,000 full-time\nemployes. Johns-Manville is trying\nto recruit 3000 veterans for additional\njobs to increase the flow of indus\ntrial products and critical building\nmaterials to consumers and dealers\nall over the country.\u201d It is then con\ntinued:\u2014\nAs Johns-Manville bent every ef\nfort to obtain more employes and\nproduce materials in the greatest\nvolume possible, a new difficulty\narose. Higher wages were advocated\nto offset supposed reductions in the\nwork week. Prices, however, were\nheld at prewar levels. There resulted\nstrikes in many industries, most of\nthem based on demands for 36 pet\ncent wage increases.\" Two of the\ncompany's largest plants still work\ning overtime schedules, it is reported,\nwere closed by strikes and remained\nclosed for four months \u2014the first\nmajor strikes in 25 years.\u201d\nProfit Margin Melts\nWith the company's selling prices\nup less than 5 per cent above the\nprewar levels, it is stated, with wages\nup more than 50 per cent and with\nth? cost of materials substantially\nhigher, the profit margin on a num\nber of products rapidly disappeared\u201d:\nthat finding it could not make a\nreasonable profit on some items and\ncould not recover costs of manufac\nturing others \"the company was\nobliged io discontinue making and\nselling several basic products. The\n1 report continues:\n\u201cNew houses are scarce largely be\ncause there is a shortage of building\nmaterials. Why? First \u2014a manpower\n1 shortage still exists, with unfilled\njobs on on? hand and unemployment\nrelief on the other. Second \u2014strikes\ncontinue to cripple production. Third\n\u2014continuance without some adjuat\nment of rigid wartime controls ham\npers (he manufacture of many Tital\nbuilding materials. Fourth \u2014certain\nMatures of the government a planned\nhousing program seem to be hinder\nng rather than helping production.\"\nFreed of unnecessary restrictions\n\u25a0and granted modest price relief on\ncritical items, the report concludes,\nthe building materials manufactur\ners of the nation can turn out enough\nmaterials to start the 1,200.00 ft hous\ning units called for in the govern\nment's housing program for 1946':\nThat in addition they can produce\nenough for several billions of dollars\nof other construction.\u201d\nA cable today reports that in com\nmenting on the labor siruation in this\nI country, the London Times in an\neditorial headed \u201cDivided .America\u2019\nI says:\nWhat in more normal times might\nhave been a purely domestic issue is\nmuch more than that to a world de\npendent as never before upon the\nI flow of American goods and the sus\nrained leadership of the United States\n'.n international affairs. Both are im\npeded as one great strike succeeds\n1 another and no settlement promises\nj to endure. Nothing in the past stormy\nfortnight suggests that either Con\ngress or the President is capable of\nunraveling this tangled skein.\n\u201cStrike votes are not taken in a\nvacuum and the great common fac\ntor to all is that th? American air\nis heavily charged with inflation. And\nthere is every indication that when\nthe Senate and the House have fin\nished tearing great holes in the price\ncontrol act. there will b? very little\nstabilization left\u201d; that \u201cthis sense\nthat it is \u2018every man fnr himself\nland devil take the hindmost\u2019 puts a\npremium upon the labor raider and\npenalizes more specific and scrupu\nlous leaders that \"it is a misfor\ntune at this moment that the Ameri\ncan labor movement is split in com\npeting bodies, each determined to\ncarrv off the richest plum.\u201d\nR. L. BARNUM.\nEARNINGS STATEMENT\nCrosley Corp.\nCincinnati, June 18\u2014(AP) \u2014Crosley\n'corp, ioday imported a net profit of\n81.453.085 for ihe year ending Decem\nber 31. 1945. equal to 81.66 per share\non outstanding capital stock. This\n[compares with revised earnings of s2.*\nh\u00ab5.529. or 54.93 a share, in the previ\nious year. Irving B. Babcock, president,\nsaid Aviation Corp., which purchased\nthe controling interest of the companv\nlast August, now owns 9<> 9 per cent\nof outstanding stock.\nSEC MATTERS\nKeleawr# Jurisdiction\nPh <d?!phia. Jun\u00ab '8 \u00abAP> Th?\ncurit es and Exchange comnri#\u00bb:on released\njur%d etit>n today over result o\u00a3 compel\nt e b dd ng m th# issue and sals by Phila\nde ph a Pa.* Electric Power Co of\n00\u00b0 of the first mortgage bond. Th# earn*\npany has accepted the bid of Kidder, Pea\nbodv Co., no. The bonds will be of\nfered public y at 102.567 per cent of prin\ncipal x?nount plus accrued interest. The\nunderwriters' commission will be .478 per\nf-ent. The Interest rate on the bonds is\n2% per cent.\nIllinois